Klaus Wilke

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
The next inspiration, you're all very familiar

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
with Jenny's keynote this morning.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And from her, I'm very inspired by the tooling,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
and we got a little bit of this this morning,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
is that she's very good at pointing out

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
how we need to focus on what's important

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
and to work towards good enough.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
And I very much like this image.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
This is from a tweet that she sent out

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
in conjunction with a paper,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
Good Enough Practices in Data Science,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
with Greg Wilson and others.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And what makes this idea so interesting

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
is that she helps provide the tools

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
to help us focus our ideas.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
And you may be familiar with the Use This Package.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
I use it extensively.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And then the Happy Git With R,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
and I think one of the best URL names ever,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.000
what they forgot to teach you about RStats.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
The third inspiration is,

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.000
if you were here last year for David Robinson's keynote,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
this helped to clarify a lot of things for me,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
is that I suppose I was a lot like Dave,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
in that I thought that things would become

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
less useful to more useful

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
as the idea became more mature.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
But in practice,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
anything that is still on your computer

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
is essentially useless.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
And anything that is off your computer

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
has got a chance.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.000
And so this was a very clarifying idea from Dave

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.000
that I'm going to try to carry through.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
And then finally, community.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:24.000
And that R-Ladies has been a great inspiration

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.000
in how to really set up an effective community.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:32.000
I hope it's okay that I single out Gabriella in this.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
Perhaps appropriate because we're in San Francisco

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.000
where she launched it.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And now, as I'm sure you know, hundreds of chapters.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And in addition to the great technical exchanges

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:46.000
that go on,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:48.000
what benefits me,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
and certainly I'm not central to this,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:55.000
is that through their amplification of voices

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
and focusing on some very important conversations,

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
it really benefits all of us.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So I wanted to point out R-Ladies

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
as a particular inspiration to me.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
So I'd like to spend the next few minutes

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
going through a particular problem

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
that we're addressing at Schneider.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
And this is to come up with a categorical color palette.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
And the challenge is that we have these brand colors

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:25.000
that are optimized for marketing,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
but they're not optimized for data visualization.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And as you may know,

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:35.000
these are two competing sets of goals here.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And from the data visualization point of view,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.000
we want to propose a related categorical palette.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
And I want to take into account color vision deficiency,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
yet still remain Schneider-y.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
And of course, Schneider-y is in the eye of the beholder,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
and particularly the UI design team

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
who will have the ultimate say on this.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
So I'm going to walk you through

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
some of the steps that we went through.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
So we start out with technique.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And as I say, the book offers some useful advice,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
and Klaus is also one of the contributors

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
to the color space package.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
And if you go on YouTube

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
and look for the UseR! talks last year,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:23.000
that Akam Xylus had a tremendously useful talk

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.000
that really helped us get on our way.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
And as a bit of a side note,

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
it was at this conference a year ago

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
that I was very fortunate to be sitting beside

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
during a session Carla Scheidegger,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
who's here this time as well.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And during the wee breaks between the presentations,

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
I got a very short course on color theory

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
that was very illuminating.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
But the upshot of it here is,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
and Will Chase talked about this a little bit this morning,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
I'll use slightly different words,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
is to think in terms of hue, chroma, and luminance

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
rather than red, green, and blue.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
And there's all these interesting paths

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
that you can go down.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
You know, for instance,

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
we start with RGB, hue, chroma, luminance,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
visible gamut, color vision deficiency,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.000
perceptual distance, it just goes on and on.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
And each of these are super interesting rabbit holes

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
that Hayley and I, we found ourselves lost in them.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
And it makes for great fun.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
And at times, you know, I think we felt like this guy.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:30.000
So what we needed is focus.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And this is where we come back to this idea of tooling.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And that we needed numbers to show perceptual differences.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
And that we began with the color space package

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:47.000
and then we're tuned in to Thomas Lynn Peterson's

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:52.000
Farver package, which can be used to quantify

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
differences between colors.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
And we decided to try to put these together

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
with a set of tools that we could use.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And this is available out on GitHub.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.000
It's called Paloval, and it's this first sort of mix

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
between color space and Farver.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
And in the spirit of the FAA certified duct tape

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
that we see here, it's good enough now.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
I hope to improve it later.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
But it got us through what we needed to do.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
It's 70% there.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
Then on to communication.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
We created an internal blog, and then using Distil,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
and we're lucky enough at Schneider Electric

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
that we have an internal instance of GitHub Enterprise.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So a lot of these, this great tooling

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
that the Tidyverse team have built for open source

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:47.000
that we can adapt within the company.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So we're able to serve this out on GitHub Enterprise.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
It's a Distil blog, another package from our studio.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:57.000
And it helps us to get our ideas out there.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And then finally, once we get the ideas out there,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
we need to seek more opinions,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
and we need to get new perspectives.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
So we're building this thing at Schneider Electric.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
Our term of art at Schneider Electric is a community at work.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:13.000
And the idea is we want it to be by practitioners for practitioners.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
That if, you know, we don't care what tool you use,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
we know that we're going to be using all different tools.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
But if we can meet and discuss what we think about

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:26.000
when we create a visualization,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
this can be a useful thing.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
And we also hope that this can be a useful point of contact

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:33.000
with the UI design team.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
So if we come up with recommendations that we hope

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
that all of these different business units can use,

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
that at least we've had a chance to discuss them amongst ourselves.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And, you know, first of all, we'll get better ideas.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:50.000
And hopefully this helps to facilitate adoption of the ideas.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
So our result is this is our first proposal here.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And this takes into account color vision deficiency.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
It's potentially Schneider-y.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And we've had some useful feedback,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
and I'll share some of it with you as I think we'll...

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.000
I'm not sure how well it's showing up on these screens,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.000
but we may in fact remove the reds.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Because for some color vision deficient folks,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
it was difficult to tell apart from the purples.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.000
And as I'm learning that red can be a very useful color

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
but can sometimes convey a sentiment

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
that you're not intending to convey.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
And with a categorical color palette,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
unless you want to say that something is...

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
really requires your attention,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.000
we might go with something that's more neutral.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:49.000
But the thing here is that we designed this using R,

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.000
but the thing that we deliver are the hex codes.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
And that the rest of Schneider, as long as it works,

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
perhaps aren't terribly concerned that we used R,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
but that what we do deliver,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:06.000
that these hex codes can be useful in all of these different tools

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
that then get used in front of the customers.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
So I'd like to spend a...

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
just to sort of wrap up with the...

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
with some ideas of other things

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
that I was thinking of putting in this talk,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
but didn't make it into the talk,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
so I call it more broadly,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
is that under technique,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
I'm very much like this idea of the grammar of graphics

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
as a description as well as a tool.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
And it's got this very handy implementation

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
that will build your chart for you,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
but for me, it helps to focus my thinking

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:45.000
and it helps me to be able to describe in very clear terms

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
to somebody who's using their own tool,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
map this variable to the x-axis,

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
map this variable to your fill color,

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
so on and so forth,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
use this type of scale.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:03.000
And this is just another way that Klaus's book

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:06.000
has been tremendously useful to us.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
In terms of tooling,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
interactivity is something that we're interested in

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
and certainly in front of our customer

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
that we're using interactive tools,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.000
and we're very interested in Vega-Lite.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
And indeed, right now,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
there's a talk by Alicia Shep,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
who's doing some super cool stuff

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
to build Vega-Lite specs,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
so please make sure you get a chance to watch that

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
when the videos are released,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
as well as Dewey Dunnington,

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
who's talking about ggplot2,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
so I really wish I could have been

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
in four places at once right now.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Perhaps three places at once.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
But Alicia and I,

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
we have an organization on GitHub on VegaWidget,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
which provides some tools

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
if you're interested in Vega-Lite

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
and interactive visualization,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
some first steps towards that.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
With communication, just to reiterate,

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
move things off of your computer,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
get them into the world.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
So nothing terribly new there.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
But this one is,

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
I think this is my secret,

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
this has been the secret

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
to a lot of my success

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
and enjoyment of my job

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
over the past six or seven years,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
is to get to know a local university.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
I am tremendously lucky

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
that I work in Iowa,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
and I'm able to visit Iowa State

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
every so often and work with Heike Hoffman.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.000
And this has led us to hire some interns,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
one of whom is here.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
I'm very glad to see her.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
As well, that led to being able to sponsor Haley

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
as a PhD student.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
So if you have a chance to get to know

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:54.000
a local university,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
maybe you run into somebody here,

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
I find that this is a way

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
to continue the spirit of this conference

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
throughout the rest of the year.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
So with that, I'm happy to

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
yield back the floor to Fareed.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
Thank you very much.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
Some links that may be useful,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
and thank you very much.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
So we have a couple of minutes for questions.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
Let me just check our Slido.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
And if you haven't submitted,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
you are welcome to stand up

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
and ask a question as well.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
One question is,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
it sounds like our team

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
ended up leading the charge

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
for something that is going to benefit

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
the entire organization,

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
a huge organization.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
Why do you think your team

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
ended up with this opportunity

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
slash responsibility,

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
and what do you think made you successful in the end?

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
Well,

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
I think we're in the right place.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
We're a central organization,

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
because each business

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
is quite rightly interested

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
in their success,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
and the success of their customers.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
One of our charters as a group

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
is to try to get all the,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
to address the interests

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
that are common to all the businesses.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
So I think we're in a good position

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
to do that.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And this has been a first step.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
I hope to report back

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
at some point

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
with all of the other

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
recommendations that we'll have made.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
But a lot of the time

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
that we had spent last year

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
was really getting our ducks in a row

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
and thinking about things

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
like communication and community

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
and essentially the four points

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
that I brought up through the slides.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
Great.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
Any other questions off the floor?

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
All right.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
Let's thank Ian. Thank you so much.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
Thank you. Really appreciate it.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
Thank you.

